label: acne keloid
semantic_ground_truth: A type of acneiform disorder in which secondary pyogenic infection in and around pilosebaceous structures ends in keloidal scarring. It manifests as persistent folliculitis of the back of the neck associated with occlusion of the follicular orifices. It is most often encountered in black or Asian men.

label: antilymphocyte serum
semantic_ground_truth: Serum containing GAMMA-GLOBULINS which are antibodies for lymphocyte ANTIGENS. It is used both as a test for HISTOCOMPATIBILITY and therapeutically in TRANSPLANTATION.
synonyms: Lymphocyte Immune Globulin, Anti Thymocyte Globulin

label: centromere
semantic_ground_truth: The clear constricted portion of the chromosome at which the chromatids are joined and by which the chromosome is attached to the spindle during cell division.

label: edible grain
semantic_ground_truth: SEEDS used as a major nutritional source, most often the grain from the POACEAE family.

label: chromatids
semantic_ground_truth: Either of the two longitudinally adjacent threads formed when a eukaryotic chromosome replicates prior to mitosis. The chromatids are held together at the centromere. Sister chromatids are derived from the same chromosome. (Singleton & Sainsbury, Dictionary of Microbiology and Molecular Biology, 2d ed)

label: chromatin
semantic_ground_truth: The material of CHROMOSOMES. It is a complex of DNA; HISTONES; and nonhistone proteins (CHROMOSOMAL PROTEINS, NON-HISTONE) found within the nucleus of a cell.

label: chromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: In a prokaryotic cell or in the nucleus of a eukaryotic cell, a structure consisting of or containing DNA which carries the genetic information essential to the cell. (From Singleton & Sainsbury, Dictionary of Microbiology and Molecular Biology, 2d ed)

label: chromosomes, bacterial
semantic_ground_truth: Structures within the nucleus of bacterial cells consisting of or containing DNA, which carry genetic information essential to the cell.

label: chromosomes, human
semantic_ground_truth: Very long DNA molecules and associated proteins, HISTONES, and non-histone chromosomal proteins (CHROMOSOMAL PROTEINS, NON-HISTONE). Normally 46 chromosomes, including two sex chromosomes are found in the nucleus of human cells. They carry the hereditary information of the individual.

label: cicatrix
semantic_ground_truth: The fibrous tissue that replaces normal tissue during the process of WOUND HEALING.

label: dental fissures
semantic_ground_truth: Naturally occurring deep grooves or clefts in the surface of teeth equivalent to class 1 cavities in Black's classification of dental caries.

label: dentin, secondary
semantic_ground_truth: Dentin formed by normal pulp after completion of root end formation.

label: egg yolk
semantic_ground_truth: Cytoplasm stored in an egg that contains nutritional reserves for the developing embryo. It is rich in polysaccharides, lipids, and proteins.

label: fruit
semantic_ground_truth: The fleshy or dry ripened ovary of a plant, enclosing the seed or seeds.

label: heterochromatin
semantic_ground_truth: The portion of chromosome material that remains condensed and is transcriptionally inactive during INTERPHASE.

label: immune sera
semantic_ground_truth: Serum that contains antibodies. It is obtained from an animal that has been immunized either by ANTIGEN injection or infection with microorganisms containing the antigen.

historical_trace.history_note: 80; was IMMUNE SERUMS 1963-79; IMMUNE SERUM GLOBULIN was heading 1965

label: inclusion bodies, viral
semantic_ground_truth: An area showing altered staining behavior in the nucleus or cytoplasm of a virus-infected cell. Some inclusion bodies represent virus factories in which viral nucleic acid or protein is being synthesized; others are merely artifacts of fixation and staining. One example, Negri bodies, are found in the cytoplasm or processes of nerve cells in animals that have died from rabies.

label: keloid
semantic_ground_truth: A sharply elevated, irregularly shaped, progressively enlarging scar resulting from formation of excessive amounts of collagen in the dermis during connective tissue repair. It is differentiated from a hypertrophic scar (CICATRIX, HYPERTROPHIC) in that the former does not spread to surrounding tissues.

label: meckel diverticulum
semantic_ground_truth: A congenital abnormality characterized by the outpouching or sac formation in the ILEUM. It is a remnant of the embryonic YOLK SAC in which the VITELLINE DUCT failed to close.

label: melena
semantic_ground_truth: The black, tarry, foul-smelling FECES that contain degraded blood.

label: milk
semantic_ground_truth: The off-white liquid secreted by the mammary glands of humans and other mammals. It contains proteins, sugar, lipids, vitamins, and minerals.

label: milk proteins
semantic_ground_truth: The major protein constituents of milk are CASEINS and whey proteins such as LACTALBUMIN and LACTOGLOBULINS. IMMUNOGLOBULINS occur in high concentrations in COLOSTRUM and in relatively lower concentrations in milk. (Singleton and Sainsbury, Dictionary of Microbiology and Molecular Biology, 2d ed, p554)

label: milk, human
semantic_ground_truth: Milk that is produced by HUMAN MAMMARY GLANDS.

label: neoplastic cells, circulating
semantic_ground_truth: Exfoliate neoplastic cells circulating in the blood and associated with metastasizing tumors.

label: nucleolus organizer region
semantic_ground_truth: The chromosome region which is active in nucleolus formation and which functions in the synthesis of ribosomal RNA.

label: nucleosomes
semantic_ground_truth: The repeating structural units of chromatin, each consisting of approximately 200 base pairs of DNA wound around a protein core. This core is composed of the histones H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.

label: nuts
semantic_ground_truth: Botanically, a type of single-seeded fruit in which the pericarp enclosing the seed is a hard woody shell. In common usage the term is used loosely for any hard, oil-rich kernel. Of those commonly eaten, only hazel, filbert, and chestnut are strictly nuts. Walnuts, pecans, almonds, and coconuts are really drupes. Brazil nuts, pistachios, macadamias, and cashews are really seeds with a hard shell derived from the testa rather than the pericarp.

label: philadelphia chromosome
semantic_ground_truth: An aberrant form of human CHROMOSOME 22 characterized by translocation of the distal end of chromosome 9 from 9q34, to the long arm of chromosome 22 at 22q11. It is present in the bone marrow cells of 80 to 90 per cent of patients with chronic myelocytic leukemia (LEUKEMIA, MYELOGENOUS, CHRONIC, BCR-ABL POSITIVE).

label: ring chromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: Aberrant chromosomes with no ends, i.e., circular.

label: seeds
semantic_ground_truth: The encapsulated embryos of flowering plants. They are used as is or for animal feed because of the high content of concentrated nutrients like starches, proteins, and fats. Rapeseed, cottonseed, and sunflower seed are also produced for the oils (fats) they yield.

historical_trace.history_note: 63; EMBRYO, PLANT was EMBRYOS, PLANT see SEEDS 1986-94

label: sex chromatin
semantic_ground_truth: In the interphase nucleus, a condensed mass of chromatin representing an inactivated X chromosome. Each X CHROMOSOME, in excess of one, forms sex chromatin (Barr body) in the mammalian nucleus. (from King & Stansfield, A Dictionary of Genetics, 4th ed)

label: sex chromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: The homologous chromosomes that are dissimilar in the heterogametic sex. There are the X CHROMOSOME, the Y CHROMOSOME, and the W, Z chromosomes (in animals in which the female is the heterogametic sex (the silkworm moth Bombyx mori, for example)). In such cases the W chromosome is the female-determining and the male is ZZ. (From King & Stansfield, A Dictionary of Genetics, 4th ed)

label: synaptonemal complex
semantic_ground_truth: The three-part structure of ribbon-like proteinaceous material that serves to align and join the paired homologous CHROMOSOMES. It is formed during the ZYGOTENE STAGE of the first meiotic division. It is a prerequisite for CROSSING OVER.

label: tooth, unerupted
semantic_ground_truth: A normal developing tooth which has not yet perforated the oral mucosa or one that fails to erupt in the normal sequence or time interval expected for the type of tooth in a given gender, age, or population group.

label: venoms
semantic_ground_truth: Poisonous animal secretions forming fluid mixtures of many different enzymes, toxins, and other substances. These substances are produced in specialized glands and secreted through specialized delivery systems (nematocysts, spines, fangs, etc.) for disabling prey or predator.

label: x chromosome
semantic_ground_truth: The female sex chromosome, being the differential sex chromosome carried by half the male gametes and all female gametes in human and other male-heterogametic species.

label: y chromosome
semantic_ground_truth: The male sex chromosome, being the differential sex chromosome carried by half the male gametes and none of the female gametes in humans and in some other male-heterogametic species in which the homologue of the X chromosome has been retained.

label: chromosomes, fungal
semantic_ground_truth: Structures within the nucleus of fungal cells consisting of or containing DNA, which carry genetic information essential to the cell.

label: telomere
semantic_ground_truth: A terminal section of a chromosome which has a specialized structure and which is involved in chromosomal replication and stability. Its length is believed to be a few hundred base pairs.

label: cell wall skeleton
semantic_ground_truth: A mucoprotein found in the cell wall of various types of bacteria. It has adjuvant and antitumor activities and has been used to augment the production of lymphokine-activated killer (LAK) cells.

label: cicatrix, hypertrophic
semantic_ground_truth: An elevated scar, resembling a KELOID, but which does not spread into surrounding tissues. It is formed by enlargement and overgrowth of cicatricial tissue and regresses spontaneously.

label: chromosomes, artificial, yeast
semantic_ground_truth: Chromosomes in which fragments of exogenous DNA ranging in length up to several hundred kilobase pairs have been cloned into yeast through ligation to vector sequences. These artificial chromosomes are used extensively in molecular biology for the construction of comprehensive genomic libraries of higher organisms.

label: kinetochores
semantic_ground_truth: Large multiprotein complexes that bind the centromeres of the chromosomes to the microtubules of the mitotic spindle during metaphase in the cell cycle.

label: isochromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: Metacentric chromosomes produced during MEIOSIS or MITOSIS when the CENTROMERE splits transversely instead of longitudinally. The chromosomes produced by this abnormal division are one chromosome having the two long arms of the original chromosome, but no short arms, and the other chromosome consisting of the two short arms and no long arms. Each of these isochromosomes constitutes a simultaneous duplication and deletion.

label: biofilms
semantic_ground_truth: Encrustations formed from microbes (bacteria, algae, fungi, plankton, or protozoa) embedded in an EXTRACELLULAR POLYMERIC SUBSTANCE MATRIX that is secreted by the microbes. They occur on body surfaces such as teeth (DENTAL DEPOSITS); inanimate objects, and bodies of water. Biofilms are prevented from forming by treating surfaces with DENTIFRICES; DISINFECTANTS; ANTI-INFECTIVE AGENTS; and anti-fouling agents.

label: chromosomes, archaeal
semantic_ground_truth: Structures within the nucleus of archaeal cells consisting of or containing DNA, which carry genetic information essential to the cell.

label: chromosome structures
semantic_ground_truth: Structures which are contained in or part of CHROMOSOMES.

label: euchromatin
semantic_ground_truth: Chromosome regions that are loosely packaged and more accessible to RNA polymerases than HETEROCHROMATIN. These regions also stain differentially in CHROMOSOME BANDING preparations.

label: chromosomes, artificial
semantic_ground_truth: DNA constructs that are composed of, at least, elements such as a REPLICATION ORIGIN; TELOMERE; and CENTROMERE, that are required for successful replication, propagation to and maintenance in progeny cells. In addition, they are constructed to carry other sequences for analysis or gene transfer.

label: chromosomes, artificial, bacterial
semantic_ground_truth: DNA constructs that are composed of, at least, a REPLICATION ORIGIN, for successful replication, propagation to and maintenance as an extra chromosome in bacteria. In addition, they can carry large amounts (about 200 kilobases) of other sequence for a variety of bioengineering purposes.

label: chromosomes, artificial, mammalian
semantic_ground_truth: DNA constructs that are composed of, at least, all elements, such as a REPLICATION ORIGIN; TELOMERE; and CENTROMERE, that are required for successful replication, propagation to and maintainance in progeny mammalian cells. In addition, they are constructed to carry other sequences for analysis or gene transfer.

label: chromosomes, artificial, human
semantic_ground_truth: DNA constructs that are composed of, at least, all elements, such as a REPLICATION ORIGIN; TELOMERE; and CENTROMERE, required for successful replication, propagation to and maintainance in progeny human cells. In addition, they are constructed to carry other sequences for analysis or gene transfer.

label: chromosomes, artificial, p1 bacteriophage
semantic_ground_truth: DNA constructs that are derived from the DNA of BACTERIOPHAGE P1. They can carry large amounts (about 100-300 kilobases) of other sequence for a variety of bioengineering purposes.

label: chromosomes, plant
semantic_ground_truth: Complex nucleoprotein structures which contain the genomic DNA and are part of the CELL NUCLEUS of PLANTS.

label: chromosomes, mammalian
semantic_ground_truth: Complex nucleoprotein structures which contain the genomic DNA and are part of the CELL NUCLEUS of MAMMALS.

label: oocysts
semantic_ground_truth: Zygote-containing cysts of sporozoan protozoa. Further development in an oocyst produces small individual infective organisms called SPOROZOITES. Then, depending on the genus, the entire oocyst is called a sporocyst or the oocyst contains multiple sporocysts encapsulating the sporozoites.

label: sporozoites
semantic_ground_truth: The product of meiotic division of zygotes in parasitic protozoa comprising haploid cells. These infective cells invade the host and undergo asexual reproduction producing MEROZOITES (or other forms) and ultimately gametocytes.

label: telomeric repeat binding protein 1
semantic_ground_truth: A ubiquitously expressed telomere-binding protein that is present at TELOMERES throughout the CELL CYCLE. It is a suppressor of telomere elongation and may be involved in stabilization of telomere length. It is structurally different from TELOMERIC REPEAT BINDING PROTEIN 2 in that it contains acidic N-terminal amino acid residues.

historical_trace.history_note: 2003; for TRF1 PROTEIN use TELOMERE-BINDING PROTEINS (NM) 1997-2002;

label: chromosomes, human, x

label: chromosomes, human, y

label: phycobilisomes
semantic_ground_truth: Light energy harvesting structures attached to the THYLAKOID MEMBRANES of CYANOBACTERIA and RED ALGAE. These multiprotein complexes contain pigments (PHYCOBILIPROTEINS) that transfer light energy to chlorophyll a.

label: micronuclei, chromosome-defective
semantic_ground_truth: Defective nuclei produced during the TELOPHASE of MITOSIS or MEIOSIS by lagging CHROMOSOMES or chromosome fragments derived from spontaneous or experimentally induced chromosomal structural changes.

keyword_candidates.term: Chromosome Defective Micronuclei statistics & numerical data

label: schizonts
semantic_ground_truth: Multinucleate cells or a stage in the development of sporozoan protozoa. It is exemplified by the life cycle of PLASMODIUM FALCIPARUM in the MALARIA infection cycle.

label: merozoites
semantic_ground_truth: Uninuclear cells or a stage in the life cycle of sporozoan protozoa. Merozoites, released from ruptured multinucleate SCHIZONTS, enter the blood stream and infect the ERYTHROCYTES.

label: trophozoites
semantic_ground_truth: Cells or feeding stage in the life cycle of sporozoan protozoa. In the malarial parasite, the trophozoite develops from the MEROZOITE and then splits into the SCHIZONT. Trophozoites that are left over from cell division can go on to form gametocytes.

label: axial length, eye
semantic_ground_truth: The distance between the anterior and posterior poles of the eye, measured either by ULTRASONOGRAPHY or by partial coherence interferometry.

label: chromosomes, insect
semantic_ground_truth: Structures within the CELL NUCLEUS of insect cells containing DNA.

label: polytene chromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: Extra large CHROMOSOMES, each consisting of many identical copies of a chromosome lying next to each other in parallel.

label: filamins
semantic_ground_truth: A family of crosslinking filament proteins encoded by distinct FLN genes. Filamins are involved in cell adhesion, spreading, and migration, acting as scaffolds for over 90 binding partners including channels, receptors, intracellular signaling molecules and transcription factors. Due to the range of molecular interactions, mutations in FLN genes result in anomalies with moderate to lethal consequences.

label: atypical squamous cells of the cervix
canonical_label: Atypical Squamous Cells of the Cervix
semantic_ground_truth: Morphological abnormalities of the cervical EPITHELIUM, usually revealed in PAP SMEAR, which do not meet the criteria for squamous CERVICAL INTRAEPITHELIAL NEOPLASIA or SQUAMOUS CELL CARCINOMAS of the CERVIX . It may be a sign of infection with certain types of human papillomavirus (HPV).or sign of a benign (not cancer) growth, such as a cyst or polyp or, in menopausal women, of low hormone levels. More testing, such as HPV test, may be needed.

label: whey
semantic_ground_truth: The liquid components of milk that remain after the CASEIN, fat, and fat soluble components have been removed. It is also a byproduct of cheese production.

label: whey proteins
semantic_ground_truth: The protein components of milk obtained from the whey.

label: buttermilk
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from cow's milk fermented by LACTIC ACID-producing bacteria, especially LACTOCOCCUS LACTIS and LACTOBACILLUS BULGARICUS.

historical_trace.history_note: 2017; use MILK 1998-2003 and CULTURED MILK PRODUCTS 2004-2016

label: kefir
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from milk fermented by a mixture of endogenous LACTIC ACID-producing yeast and bacteria (KEFIR GRAINS), many of which are PROBIOTICS. It should not be confused with KAFFIR LIME or KAFFIR CORN.

historical_trace.history_note: 2017; use MILK 1998-2003 and CULTURED MILK PRODUCTS 2004-2016

label: koumiss
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from horse's milk that is fermented by endogenous LACTIC ACID-producing bacteria and ETHANOL-producing yeast.

label: pseudoautosomal regions
semantic_ground_truth: Homologous chromosomal regions at either end of the X CHROMOSOME or Y CHROMOSOME. These two regions pair regularly at male MEIOSIS and undergo RECOMBINATION. Pseudoautosomal region 1 (PAR1) is located  at the tip of the short 'p' arms (Xp22 and Yp11) and Pseudoautosomal region 2 (PAR2) is located at the tip of the long 'q' arms (Xq28 and Yq12).

label: margins of excision
semantic_ground_truth: The edges of tissue removed in a surgery for assessment of the effectiveness of a surgical procedure in achieving the local control of a neoplasm and the adequacy of tumor removal. When the margin is negative or not involved by tumor (e.g., CANCER) it suggests all of the tumor has been removed by the surgery.

label: tertiary lymphoid structures
semantic_ground_truth: Aggregates of immune cells formed near the sites of chronically inflamed, infected, or tumorous tissues.

label: extracellular polymeric substance matrix
semantic_ground_truth: Extracellular matrix formed by secreted polymeric organic compounds by microorganisms. This secreted compound is mostly polysaccharides but may include proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids. The matrix facilitates attachment of microbes to form various BIOFILM communities.

label: viral replication compartments
semantic_ground_truth: Sites in the host cell where the virus induces the formation of cellular assemblies for the replication of the VIRAL GENOME.

label: secretome
semantic_ground_truth: The set of all the soluble factors and extracellular vesicles secreted into the extracellular space by cells, or an organ or organism. In some studies the secretome only refers to the proteins secreted into the extracellular space.

label: shelterin complex
semantic_ground_truth: A TELOMERE cap complex consisting of telomere-specific proteins in association with telomeric DNA such as telomeric dsDNA-sDNA junction. They are involved in the protection of chromosome ends and TELOMERASE regulation and play a role in CELLULAR SENESCENCE and ageing-related pathology. In general it consists of six mostly TELOMERE-BINDING PROTEINS (POT1, RAP1, TIN2, TPP1, TRF1, and TRF2).

label: decellularized extracellular matrix
semantic_ground_truth: A biomaterial with a network of macromolecules with varying composition and organization of tissue-specific proteins and polysaccharides. It is prepared from organs and tissues by decellularization (e.g., with a detergent) to mimic native microenvironment for tissue-specific functions.

label: microphysiological systems
semantic_ground_truth: Devices designed to recapitulate tissue or organ-level physiology and architect by combining MICROFLUIDICS; MICROFABRICATION; and 3D CELL CULTURE. Microphysiological systems mimic interconnections important in physiological or pathophysiological states of organ(s) and are often used for instance in HIGH THROUGHPUT SCREENING of drugs and factors important in disease modeling.

label: edible grain

label: oocysts

label: sporozoites

label: schizonts

label: trophozoites
semantic_ground_truth: Cells or feeding stage in the life cycle of sporozoan protozoa. In the malarial parasite, the trophozoite develops from the MEROZOITE and then splits into the SCHIZONT. Trophozoites that are left over from cell division can go on to form gametocytes.

label: acne keloid

label: keloid

label: melena

label: micronuclei, chromosome-defective
semantic_ground_truth: Defective nuclei produced during the TELOPHASE of MITOSIS or MEIOSIS by lagging CHROMOSOMES or chromosome fragments derived from spontaneous or experimentally induced chromosomal structural changes.

label: schizonts
semantic_ground_truth: Multinucleate cells or a stage in the development of sporozoan protozoa. It is exemplified by the life cycle of PLASMODIUM FALCIPARUM in the MALARIA infection cycle.

label: merozoites
semantic_ground_truth: Uninuclear cells or a stage in the life cycle of sporozoan protozoa. Merozoites, released from ruptured multinucleate SCHIZONTS, enter the blood stream and infect the ERYTHROCYTES.

label: trophozoites
semantic_ground_truth: Cells or feeding stage in the life cycle of sporozoan protozoa. In the malarial parasite, the trophozoite develops from the MEROZOITE and then splits into the SCHIZONT. Trophozoites that are left over from cell division can go on to form gametocytes.

label: chromosomes, insect
semantic_ground_truth: Structures within the CELL NUCLEUS of insect cells containing DNA.

label: polytene chromosomes
semantic_ground_truth: Extra large CHROMOSOMES, each consisting of many identical copies of a chromosome lying next to each other in parallel.

label: whey
semantic_ground_truth: The liquid components of milk that remain after the CASEIN, fat, and fat soluble components have been removed. It is also a byproduct of cheese production.

label: whey proteins
semantic_ground_truth: The protein components of milk obtained from the whey.

label: buttermilk
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from cow's milk fermented by LACTIC ACID-producing bacteria, especially LACTOCOCCUS LACTIS and LACTOBACILLUS BULGARICUS.

label: kefir
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from milk fermented by a mixture of endogenous LACTIC ACID-producing yeast and bacteria (KEFIR GRAINS), many of which are PROBIOTICS. It should not be confused with KAFFIR LIME or KAFFIR CORN.

historical_trace.history_note: 2017; use MILK 1998-2003 and CULTURED MILK PRODUCTS 2004-2016

label: koumiss
semantic_ground_truth: A beverage made from horse's milk that is fermented by endogenous LACTIC ACID-producing bacteria and ETHANOL-producing yeast.

label: pseudoautosomal regions
semantic_ground_truth: Homologous chromosomal regions at either end of the X CHROMOSOME or Y CHROMOSOME. These two regions pair regularly at male MEIOSIS and undergo RECOMBINATION. Pseudoautosomal region 1 (PAR1) is located  at the tip of the short 'p' arms (Xp22 and Yp11) and Pseudoautosomal region 2 (PAR2) is located at the tip of the long 'q' arms (Xq28 and Yq12).

label: extracellular polymeric substance matrix
semantic_ground_truth: Extracellular matrix formed by secreted polymeric organic compounds by microorganisms. This secreted compound is mostly polysaccharides but may include proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids. The matrix facilitates attachment of microbes to form various BIOFILM communities.

label: secretome
semantic_ground_truth: The set of all the soluble factors and extracellular vesicles secreted into the extracellular space by cells, or an organ or organism. In some studies the secretome only refers to the proteins secreted into the extracellular space.

label: shelterin complex
semantic_ground_truth: A TELOMERE cap complex consisting of telomere-specific proteins in association with telomeric DNA such as telomeric dsDNA-sDNA junction. They are involved in the protection of chromosome ends and TELOMERASE regulation and play a role in CELLULAR SENESCENCE and ageing-related pathology. In general it consists of six mostly TELOMERE-BINDING PROTEINS (POT1, RAP1, TIN2, TPP1, TRF1, and TRF2).

label: egg yolk
semantic_ground_truth: Cytoplasm stored in an egg that contains nutritional reserves for the developing embryo. It is rich in polysaccharides, lipids, and proteins.

label: milk proteins

label: nuts
semantic_ground_truth: Botanically, a type of single-seeded fruit in which the pericarp enclosing the seed is a hard woody shell. In common usage the term is used loosely for any hard, oil-rich kernel. Of those commonly eaten, only hazel, filbert, and chestnut are strictly nuts. Walnuts, pecans, almonds, and coconuts are really drupes. Brazil nuts, pistachios, macadamias, and cashews are really seeds with a hard shell derived from the testa rather than the pericarp.

label: seeds
semantic_ground_truth: The encapsulated embryos of flowering plants. They are used as is or for animal feed because of the high content of concentrated nutrients like starches, proteins, and fats. Rapeseed, cottonseed, and sunflower seed are also produced for the oils (fats) they yield.
